Historical Note
The New York Foundation for the Arts (NYFA) was founded in 1971 in New York City by a group of artists who were part of the New York State Department of Cultural Affairs (NYSCA). Their goal was to create an organization that would provide artists like themselves with resources guidance and funding for their art projects that NYSCA could not provide directly. NYFA grew over the decades to become one of the leading organizations providing grants and services in New York City, New York State, and in the country. NYFA's programs are dedicated to providing guidance and support for artists and smaller arts organizations seeking city, state, and federal organization funding.

Scope and Contents
The New York Foundation for the Arts Records consists of the organization's materials for close to 50 years. The materials highlight the organization's mission to fulfill its vision in empowering emerging artists and arts organizations across all creative disciplines. The collection begins with administrative materials under Human Resources that detail committee meetings and retreats, employee handbooks and position descriptions, and office space contracts for other organization's sharing work space with NYFA. Board materials include agenda packets with meeting minutes, memorandum, and executive reports written by Ted Berger. Ted Berger's paper collection during his stint as Executive Director for NYFA is also included along with the Board's collection. The Development department's documents provide marketing materials for the annual fund, as well as NYSCA reports, and correspondence. The Finance department contributes its annual financial reports in generated in documenting the organization's yearly budget and loss, payroll, and tax returns. The Communications department adds to the mix of documents with outreach materials such as general brochures, publications, and original printed materials in support of NYFA programs made available to artists and arts organizations. A bulk of NYFA's records consist of grant applications and materials submitted by artists and arts organizations for opportunities that support the development of artists fellowships, individual and organizational art projects, arts in education implementation initiatives, and disaster relief and wage subsidy programs for events like 9/11 and Hurricane Sandy. These grant applications were also submitted to NYFA for opportunities in technology implementation by artists and arts organizations and artists' grants and cultural mission trips in Israel.

Processing Information
Originally, files and audio/visual material were boxed up in the NYFA offices every couple of years and sent to storage with minimal descriptions. Most of these files are arranged chronologically, but there are scattered "miscellaneous" boxes. Materials were usually grouped by program, including Artist Fellowship, Fiscal Sponsorship, Strategic Opportunity Stipends , New York Arts Recovery Fund, among others. There are also boxes of unorganized founding files, accumulated by the first director of the organization, Theodore S. Berger. Various administrative NYFA files exist, but are not in any particular order.

Scope and Contents
This subseries consists of materials created and collected by NYFA documenting the organization's Fiscal Sponsorship program from the 1970s through the early 2000s. Materials in this subseries include internal correspondence, memoranda, financial records, applications and registration forms, and research materials concerning the economic climate of the early 2000s. Individual applications consist of organization descriptions; project narrative proposals; proposed budgets; and documentation of proposed timelines, audiences, promotional plans, and fundraising strategies. Materials in this series document the methods by which NYFA provides resources to support working artists and arts organizations, and the larger context of non-profit programming to foster artistic and creative projects. The series also demonstrates the breadth of artistic projects supported through the program, including visual arts, theater, dance, film, performance art, literature, and inter-disciplinary works.Subseries A. Scope and Contents
This subseries consists of program and development information through correspondence, memorandum, and research notes for Arts in Education; Technical Assistance Program (TAP) application forms and panelists' recommendation forms; Artists in the School Community applications forms and panelists' recommendation forms; Artists and Teachers Partnership for Excellence Multiple Intelligences Project post- and pre-tests forms, including teacher comments and state education department information for schools under registration review (SED-SURR); Design Education Initiative resources, which include external information from various institutions in collaboration NYFA utilized to create the program; and correspondence and memorandum for the New York City Music Initiative, creating a timeline of the program.
Arrangement
The subseries is arranged based on the programs under Arts in Education, as mentioned in the scope and content note. TAP and Artists in the School Community applications are alphabetically and chronologically arranged. Multiple Intelligences Project, Design Education Initiative Resources, and New York City Music Initiative materials are arranged chronologically.
